# services-explained.tflw — SPEC §3.2: a `tflw.config` `env` block can declare more than one
# named API service, each with its own base URL. `api <METHOD> ...` (no name) targets the
# default service; `api <name> <METHOD> ...` targets a named one. This repo's tflw.config
# declares `root` alongside the default — same app, different base URL (no `/v1` prefix baked
# in) — so a test can prove the prefix is a real routing boundary, not just a convention.

@examples @services
test "the default (unnamed) service targets the /v1-prefixed base URL"
  api GET /health
  expect status equals 200
  expect body.status equals "ok"

@examples @services
test "the named `root` service targets the same app without the /v1 prefix"
  api root GET /health
  # /v1/health exists; /health (unversioned) doesn't — proves these are two genuinely different
  # base URLs, not just a naming convenience.
  expect status equals 404
